total success... where would we be today?<br>
<br>
Moon, Mars colonies?  Bases on the satellites of Jupiter and Saturn?<br>
Thriving asteroid mining industry? <br>
<br>
Obviously more than one 10,000 ton class launch would be a big problem<br>
in todays ecologically minded society (not that that's a bad thing)...<br>
but if the 10,000 ton ship was able to loft the industrial capability<br>
into orbit that would allow the construction of more Orion type<br>
NPR's, say circa 1972... what do you think the state of the space<br>
program would be 30 years later in 2002?<br>
<br>
What IF...? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/11/02 10:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> It would be better than it is now. But that's a really bit what if. What if Project Orion caused massive damage, and people boycotted it's infulstrucure because of it. Also, remember the first Orion wasn't for industry, it was for exploration. It's only recently that the idea for industry in space has came around... What if's can be dangerous though... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 461<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/12/02 7:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> What if's can be dangerous though... <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What if's are the basis of a good chess player.  Seriously though, the idea is that the infrastructure would be built in space for more Orions by the first Orion launch, so the NPR industry is moved off Earth... protesting it on Earth would be pointless as the one and only launch would have already occured... at least in my 'what if...'<br>
<br>
If Orions were built and launched from Earth on a regular basis, say like the Space Shuttle program... maybe 6 flights a year, then that would definitely be a BIG problem ecologically speaking and probably wouldn't last more then 2-3 launches before public outcry put a stop to it, if it was public knowledge that is. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 431<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/12/02 9:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> I think it'd be pretty hard to keep an Orion project quite.  At least once you start launching. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 937<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/14/02 7:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> The atomic bomb testing of the 60's would have increased. Personally I think this would be a negligible increase. Small devices were to be used. In comparison to the ever larger megaton devices for weapons, pulse units were tiny. <br>
Several Orions would have been launched. Each better than the previous model. Enormous amounts of research would have gone into cleaner and more efficient bomblets. <br>
This technology would then stir further developments in other fields. Several or all of these might happen. <br>
1. A reusable orbital vehicle for rotating crews would be necessary as Orions can't land.<br>
The adsvantage being that fuel could be picked up at the Orion and therefore less fuel would be needed for missions. Drastically improving performance and increasing weight allowances. <br>
2. A space elevator is built to rotate crews. <br>
An asteroid is brought back to Earth during an Orion mission to serve as ballast. This is assuming that suitable fibres are developed.<br>
3. Space factories are built.<br>
Using space resources, Orion crews put together masssive habitats and space industry becomes a reality. This wouuld give further impetus to cheap affordable space access in the form of orbital vehicles to reach Orions. This event would prelude space built Orions. By this time we would have human bases on most stable moons and planets. Possibly a colony on the moon and even Mars. <br>
<br>
Assuming an extensive Orion program back in the 60's I would predict the first Mars mission by 65 and Saturn by 70. I have faith in the predictions of the team working back then.<br>
Having proved it possible and achieving so much in so little time I doubt the public would lose interest as they did with Nasa's ho hum chemical rocket program. Back then the space administration envisioned moonbases and that has always been one of their goals. I therefore expect the second mission would be a lunar base. The first would be a flag ceremony like Apollo. Perhaps by 64. Several missions might run concurrently. If Mars is slated for 65 however then a moonbase would probably be completed by 64.<br>
Jerry Pournelle is quoted as saying Orion could establish a large moonbase  in a single shot.<br>
Having achieved a permanent presence on the moon it would only be natural to attempt colonisation within a decade or two. The entire solar system would be explored by 1980 I expect so we would know far more about Planetology and asteroids than we do in fact know in reality here in 2002.<br>
Many kinds of ship other than Orions will be built and tested without fear of polluting the space environment. Reactor rockets and anything else you like. No red tape would exist such as there is down here on Earth now. Americium rockets would doubtless be explored and developed. Space would be big buisness so big corporations would be forking out massive development grants.<br>
By 1990 the solar system would be totally colonised. Tourism would be big business but mining corporations would be plying the space lanes aswell. Farming would be at some stage of development. First started to generate self sufficiency then perhaps exported. Hollowwed out asteroids might even feed the third world. <br>
By 2000 space travel will be routine. Cities would exist all over the solar system and humaanity would be thinking about the stars. A few ships will probably already be on their way to neighbouring star systems. We'd know which ones were worth visiting because space industry had made super massive reflector telescopes a reality. We would know if intelligent life existed nearby.<br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/14/02 8:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> Hmmm.... It's possible, but I doubt it. The space elevator concept is being tested right now, and there are a few people who want to see it done. The problem is they would have to use carbon nano-tubes, and we don't really have the technology for that. Only carbon nano-tubes are light and strong enough to support it's own weight plus extra weight for a space elevator. Don't get me wrong. If Orion was successful, there is little doubt that we'd have more precence in space. But I don't think it is quite as much as your leading it to be. And fission bombs are not neglicatable. In fact, there are people to this day in Hiroshema who die because the background radiation is still very strong from the use of the nuclear bomb there, and that was only a single one. Granted that ground zero would probably not be inhabited, but still, anything more than a launch or two of Orion really begins to add up. Remember, most of the radiation from a thermonuclear bomb is in it's fission trigger, so they are almost as radation poluting as a fission bomb. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 952<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/18/02 3:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What IF...?</span><hr size=1> I think it would be a far greater presence than I described. We would have walked on every world capable of supporting a suited human. Once space resources are accessible space becomes more than just a destination. Instead of a goal it becomes routine. Somewhere to 'return' to. People would live in space. Work there and go on holidays. <br>
Orion would have made space industry a reality overnight. Colonisation is the next logical step. The resources to live there are in abundance. Getting enough initial setup material off Earth to get the ball rolling is all you need to do. <br>
All the sciences would benefit from the technological spinoffs which cant even be predicted. We would have first hand knoowledge of other bodies in space. Not unreliable soil testers on flimsy tin can probes but men with real tools prospecting those surfaces and checking below the surface too.<br>
